3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC calculates funding rates every 8 hours at 00:00, 08:00, and 16:00 UTC based on the premium between perpetual and spot prices. Long positions pay funding when rates are positive, while shorts receive payments. The exchange's zero maker fee structure reduces the cost basis for delta-neutral arbitrage positions across funding periods."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","MATIC","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MATIC/USDT represents one of the largest Layer 2 tokens by market cap, generating substantial perpetual futures volume during ecosystem developments. The pair's funding rates often spike during Polygon network upgrades, DeFi protocol launches, or broader Layer 2 narrative cycles, creating arbitrage opportunities."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MATIC funding rates on MEXC typically range from -0.1% to +0.3% per 8-hour period, with extreme spikes reaching ±1% during major announcements. The token shows increased funding volatility during Ethereum congestion periods when Layer 2 adoption accelerates. Seasonal patterns emerge around quarterly Polygon ecosystem updates and major DeFi protocol migrations to the network."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC's zero maker fees create favorable conditions for delta-neutral funding rate arbitrage on MATIC/USDT. Traders can capture funding payments by going long perpetuals and short spot across multiple exchanges when rates exceed 0.1% per period. The 8-hour funding frequency allows for three collection opportunities daily, though position management costs must be factored against potential returns."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC's order book depth for MATIC/USDT can be thinner compared to tier-1 exchanges, increasing slippage risk during volatile periods. The exchange's regulatory status may limit institutional participation, affecting liquidity during stress events. Funding rate arbitrage positions require careful monitoring of cross-exchange basis risk, especially during Polygon network events that can cause temporary price divergences."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How often does MEXC charge funding fees on MATIC/USDT perpetuals?","answer":"MEXC charges funding fees every 8 hours at 00:00, 08:00, and 16:00 UTC. This tri-daily schedule provides three opportunities to collect funding payments, though rates are calculated based on the 8-hour premium between perpetual and index prices."},{"question":"What makes MEXC competitive for MATIC funding rate arbitrage?","answer":"MEXC offers zero maker fees on MATIC/USDT perpetuals, reducing the cost of maintaining delta-neutral positions. Combined with their early listing of trending tokens and high leverage options up to 125x, this creates favorable conditions for funding rate strategies."},{"question":"Are there volume requirements for zero maker fees on MATIC perpetuals?","answer":"MEXC's zero maker fee structure applies to all users regardless of trading volume, making it accessible for smaller arbitrage operations. However, taker fees remain at 0.03%, so limit orders are essential for cost-effective funding rate arbitrage strategies."},{"question":"How volatile are MATIC funding rates during Polygon ecosystem events?","answer":"MATIC funding rates can spike significantly during major Polygon announcements, often exceeding 0.5% per 8-hour period. Network upgrades, major DApp launches, or institutional adoption news typically drive increased long interest and higher funding costs for leveraged positions."}]}]
